# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geologic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geologic/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:geologic/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:geologic/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:geologic/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:geologic/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:geologic/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:geologic/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:geologic/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:geologic/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:geologic/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:geologic/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:geologic/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:geologic/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:geologic/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:geologic/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:geologic/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:geologic/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:geologic/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:geologic/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:geologic/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:geologic/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:geologic/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:geologic/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:geologic/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:geologic/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:geologic/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:geologic/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:geologic/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:geologic/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:geologic/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:geologic/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:geologic/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:geologic/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:geologic/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:geologic/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:geologic/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:geologic/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:geologic/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:geologic/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:geologic/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:geologic/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:geologic/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:geologic/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:geologic/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:geologic/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:geologic/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:geologic/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:geologic/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:geologic/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:geologic/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:geologic/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:geologic/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:geologic/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:geologic/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:geologic/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:geologic/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:geologic/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:geologic/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:geologic/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:geologic/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:geologic/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:geologic/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:geologic/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:geologic/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:geologic/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:geologic/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:geologic/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:geologic/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:geologic/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:geologic/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:geologic/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:geologic/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:geologic/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:geologic/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:geologic/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:geologic/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:geologic/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:geologic/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:geologic/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:geologic/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:geologic/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:geologic/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:geologic/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:geologic/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:geologic/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:geologic/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:geologic/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:geologic/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:geologic/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:geologic/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geology describes the structure of the Earth on and beneath its surface and the processes that have shaped that structure.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geologists study the mineralogical composition of rocks in order to get insight into their history of formation.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geology determines the relative ages of rocks found at a given location; geochemistry (a branch of geology) determines their absolute ages.
[src:geologic/geologic] By combining various petrological, crystallographic, and paleontological tools, geologists are able to chronicle the geological history of the Earth as a whole.
[src:geologic/geologic] One aspect is to demonstrate the age of the Earth.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geology provides evidence for plate tectonics, the evolutionary history of life, and the Earth's past climates.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geologists broadly study the properties and processes of Earth and other terrestrial planets.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geologists use a wide variety of methods to understand the Earth's structure and evolution, including fieldwork, rock description, geophysical techniques, chemical analysis, physical experiments, and numerical modelling.
[src:geologic/geologic] In practical terms, geology is important for mineral and hydrocarbon exploration and exploitation, evaluating water resources, understanding natural hazards, remediating environmental problems, and providing insights into past climate change.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geology is a major academic discipline, and it is central to geological engineering and plays an important role in geotechnical engineering.
[src:geologic/geologic] The majority of geological data comes from research on solid Earth materials.
[src:geologic/geologic] Meteorites and other extraterrestrial natural materials are also studied by geological methods.
[src:geologic/geologic] Minerals are naturally occurring elements and compounds with a definite homogeneous chemical composition and an ordered atomic arrangement.
[src:geologic/geologic] Amorphous substances that resemble a mineral are sometimes referred to as mineraloids, although there are exceptions such as georgeite and autunite.
[src:geologic/geologic] Some amorphous substances formed by geological processes are considered minerals if the original substance was a mineral before metamictisation.
[src:geologic/geologic] Each mineral has distinct physical properties, and there are many tests to determine each of them.
[src:geologic/geologic] Minerals are often identified through these tests.
[src:geologic/geologic] A rock is any naturally occurring solid mass or aggregate of minerals or mineraloids.
[src:geologic/geologic] Most research in geology is associated with the study of rocks, as they provide the primary record of the majority of the geological history of the Earth.
[src:geologic/geologic] There are three major types of rock: igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic.
[src:geologic/geologic] The rock cycle illustrates the relationships among them (see diagram).
[src:geologic/geologic] When a rock solidifies or crystallizes from melt (magma or lava), it is an igneous rock.
[src:geologic/geologic] The active flow of molten rock is closely studied in volcanology, and igneous petrology aims to determine the history of igneous rocks from their original molten source to their final crystallization.
[src:geologic/geologic] Rocks can be weathered and eroded, then redeposited and lithified into a sedimentary rock.
[src:geologic/geologic] Sedimentary rocks are mainly divided into four categories: sandstone, shale, carbonate, and evaporite.
[src:geologic/geologic] This group of classifications focuses partly on the size of sedimentary particles (sandstone and shale), and partly on mineralogy and formation processes (carbonation and evaporation).
[src:geologic/geologic] Igneous and sedimentary rocks can then be turned into metamorphic rocks by heat and pressure that change its mineral content, resulting in a characteristic fabric.
[src:geologic/geologic] All three types may melt again, and when this happens, new magma is formed, from which an igneous rock may once again solidify.
[src:geologic/geologic] Organic matter, such as coal, bitumen, oil, and natural gas, is linked mainly to organic-rich sedimentary rocks.
[src:geologic/geologic] To study all three types of rock, geologists evaluate the minerals of which they are composed and their other physical properties, such as texture and fabric.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geologists study unlithified materials (referred to as *superficial deposits*) that lie above the bedrock.
[src:geologic/geologic] This study is often known as Quaternary geology, after the Quaternary period of geologic history, which is the most recent period of geologic time.
[src:geologic/geologic] In the 1960s, it was discovered that the Earth's lithosphere, which includes the crust and rigid uppermost portion of the upper mantle, is separated into tectonic plates that move across the plastically deforming, solid, upper mantle, which is called the asthenosphere.
[src:geologic/geologic] This theory is supported by several types of observations, including seafloor spreading and the global distribution of mountain terrain and seismicity.
[src:geologic/geologic] There is an intimate coupling between the movement of the plates on the surface and the convection of the mantle (that is, the heat transfer caused by the slow movement of ductile mantle rock).
[src:geologic/geologic] Thus, oceanic parts of plates and the adjoining mantle convection currents always move in the same direction – because the oceanic lithosphere is actually the rigid upper thermal boundary layer of the convecting mantle.
[src:geologic/geologic] This coupling between rigid plates moving on the surface of the Earth and the convecting mantle is called plate tectonics.
[src:geologic/geologic] The development of plate tectonics has provided a physical basis for many observations of the solid Earth.
[src:geologic/geologic] Plate tectonics has provided a mechanism for Alfred Wegener's theory of continental drift, in which the continents move across the surface of the Earth over geological time.
[src:geologic/geologic] They provided a driving force for crustal deformation, and a new setting for the observations of structural geology.
[src:geologic/geologic] The power of the theory of plate tectonics lies in its ability to combine all of these observations into a single theory of how the lithosphere moves over the convecting mantle, forming a "grand unifying theory of geology".
[src:geologic/geologic] Advances in seismology, computer modeling, and mineralogy and crystallography at high temperatures and pressures give insights into the internal composition and structure of the Earth.
[src:geologic/geologic] Seismologists can use the arrival times of seismic waves to image the interior of the Earth.
[src:geologic/geologic] Early advances in this field showed the existence of a liquid outer core (where shear waves were not able to propagate) and a dense solid inner core.
[src:geologic/geologic] These advances led to the development of a layered model of the Earth, with a lithosphere (including crust) on top, the mantle below (separated within itself by seismic discontinuities at 410 and 660 kilometers), and the outer core and inner core below that.
[src:geologic/geologic] Starting in the 1970s, seismologists have been able to use new techniques such as seismic full-waveform inversion to create detailed images of wave speeds inside the earth in the same way a doctor images a body in a CT scan.
[src:geologic/geologic] These images have led to a much more detailed view of the interior of the Earth, and have replaced the simplified layered model with a much more dynamic model.
[src:geologic/geologic] Mineralogists have been able to use the pressure and temperature data from the seismic and modeling studies alongside knowledge of the elemental composition of the Earth to reproduce these conditions in experimental settings and measure changes within the crystal structure.
[src:geologic/geologic] These studies explain the chemical changes associated with the major seismic discontinuities in the mantle and show the crystallographic structures expected in the inner core of the Earth.
[src:geologic/geologic] The geological time scale encompasses the history of the Earth.
[src:geologic/geologic] It is bracketed at the earliest by the dates of the first Solar System material at 4.567 Ga (or 4.567 billion years ago) and the formation of the Earth at 4.54 Ga (4.54 billion years), which is the beginning of the Hadean eon – a division of geological time.
[src:geologic/geologic] At the later end of the scale, it is marked by the present day (in the Holocene epoch).
[src:geologic/geologic] The following five timelines show the geologic time scale to scale.
[src:geologic/geologic] The first shows the entire time from the formation of Earth to the present, but this gives little space for the most recent eon.
[src:geologic/geologic] The second timeline shows an expanded view of the most recent eon.
[src:geologic/geologic] In a similar way, the most recent era is expanded in the third timeline, the most recent period is expanded in the fourth timeline, and the most recent epoch is expanded in the fifth timeline.
[src:geologic/geologic] The epochs of lunar history are based on the chronology of impact events, and they are named after defining major impacts.
[src:geologic/geologic] Hence, the Imbrian is named after the formation of the Mare Imbrium basin.
[src:geologic/geologic] The ages of older lunar basins can be dated based on the strength of their intrinsic magnetic field, since the early Moon had a magnetic field that faded over time.
[src:geologic/geologic] The ages of craters can be estimated by morphological and stratigraphic classifications, with younger craters overlapping older impacts and generally showing less impact wear.
[src:geologic/geologic] Methods for relative dating were developed when geology first emerged as a natural science.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geologists still use the following principles today as a means to provide information about geological history and the timing of geological events.
[src:geologic/geologic] The *principle of uniformitarianism* states that the geological processes observed in operation that modify the Earth's crust at present have worked in much the same way over geological time.
[src:geologic/geologic] The *principle of intrusive relationships* concerns crosscutting intrusions.
[src:geologic/geologic] In geology, when an igneous intrusion cuts across a formation of sedimentary rock, it can be determined that the igneous intrusion is younger than the sedimentary rock.
[src:geologic/geologic] Different types of intrusions include stocks, laccoliths, batholiths, sills and dikes.
[src:geologic/geologic] The *principle of cross-cutting relationships* pertains to the formation of faults and the age of the sequences through which they cut.
[src:geologic/geologic] Faults are younger than the rocks they cut; accordingly, if a fault is found that penetrates some formations but not those on top of it, then the formations that were cut are older than the fault, and the ones that are not cut must be younger than the fault.
[src:geologic/geologic] Finding the key bed in these situations may help determine whether the fault is a normal fault or a thrust fault.
[src:geologic/geologic] The *principle of inclusions and components* states that, with sedimentary rocks, if inclusions (or *clasts*) are found in a formation, then the inclusions must be older than the formation that contains them.
[src:geologic/geologic] For example, in sedimentary rocks, it is common for gravel from an older formation to be ripped up and included in a newer layer.
[src:geologic/geologic] A similar situation with igneous rocks occurs when xenoliths are found.
[src:geologic/geologic] These foreign bodies are picked up as magma or lava flows, and are incorporated, later to cool in the matrix.
[src:geologic/geologic] As a result, xenoliths are older than the rock that contains them.
[src:geologic/geologic] The *principle of original horizontality* states that the deposition of sediments occurs as essentially horizontal beds.
[src:geologic/geologic] Observation of modern marine and non-marine sediments in a wide variety of environments supports this generalization (although cross-bedding is inclined, the overall orientation of cross-bedded units is horizontal).
[src:geologic/geologic] The *principle of superposition* states that a sedimentary rock layer in a tectonically undisturbed sequence is younger than the one beneath it and older than the one above it.
[src:geologic/geologic] Logically a younger layer cannot slip beneath a layer previously deposited.
[src:geologic/geologic] This principle allows sedimentary layers to be viewed as a form of the vertical timeline, a partial or complete record of the time elapsed from deposition of the lowest layer to deposition of the highest bed.
[src:geologic/geologic] The *principle of faunal succession* is based on the appearance of fossils in sedimentary rocks.
[src:geologic/geologic] As organisms exist during the same period throughout the world, their presence or (sometimes) absence provides a relative age of the formations where they appear.
[src:geologic/geologic] Based on principles that William Smith laid out almost a hundred years before the publication of Charles Darwin's theory of evolution, the principles of succession developed independently of evolutionary thought.
[src:geologic/geologic] The principle becomes quite complex, however, given the uncertainties of fossilization, localization of fossil types due to lateral changes in habitat (facies change in sedimentary strata), and that not all fossils formed globally at the same time.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geologists use methods to determine the absolute age of rock samples and geological events.
[src:geologic/geologic] These may be used in conjunction with relative dating methods or to calibrate relative methods.
[src:geologic/geologic] At the beginning of the 20th century, advancement in geological science was facilitated by the ability to obtain accurate absolute dates to geological events using radioactive isotopes and other methods.
[src:geologic/geologic] This changed the understanding of geological time.
[src:geologic/geologic] Previously, geologists could only use fossils and stratigraphic correlation to date sections of rock relative to one another.
[src:geologic/geologic] With isotopic dates, it became possible to assign absolute ages to rock units, and these absolute dates could be applied to fossil sequences in which there was datable material, converting the old relative ages into new absolute ages.
[src:geologic/geologic] These are used in geochronologic and thermochronologic studies.
[src:geologic/geologic] The most suitable isotope systems for this purpose include uranium–lead, rubidium–strontium, and potassium–argon.
[src:geologic/geologic] Uranium–thorium dating is used for dating calcium-carbonate.
[src:geologic/geologic] Dating of lava and volcanic ash layers found within a stratigraphic sequence can provide absolute age data for sedimentary rock units that do not contain radioactive isotopes and calibrate relative dating techniques.
[src:geologic/geologic] These methods can be used to determine ages of pluton emplacement.
[src:geologic/geologic] Fractionation of the lanthanide series elements is used to compute ages since rocks were removed from the mantle.
[src:geologic/geologic] Other methods are used for more recent events.
[src:geologic/geologic] Optically stimulated luminescence and cosmogenic radionuclide dating are used to date surfaces and/or erosion rates.
[src:geologic/geologic] Dendrochronology can be used for the dating of landscapes.
[src:geologic/geologic] Radiocarbon dating is used for geologically young materials containing organic carbon.
[src:geologic/geologic] Thermochemical techniques can be used to determine temperature profiles within the crust, the uplift of mountain ranges, and paleo-topography.
[src:geologic/geologic] The geology of an area changes through time as rock units are deposited and inserted, and deformational processes alter their shapes and locations.
[src:geologic/geologic] Rock units are first emplaced either by deposition onto the surface or intrusion into the overlying rock.
[src:geologic/geologic] Deposition can occur when sediments settle onto the surface of the Earth and later lithify into sedimentary rock, or when as volcanic material such as volcanic ash or lava flows blanket the surface.
[src:geologic/geologic] Igneous intrusions such as batholiths, laccoliths, dikes, and sills, push upwards into the overlying rock, and crystallize as they intrude.
[src:geologic/geologic] After the initial sequence of rocks has been deposited, the rock units can be deformed and/or metamorphosed.
[src:geologic/geologic] Deformation typically occurs as a result of horizontal shortening, horizontal extension, or side-to-side (strike-slip) motion.
[src:geologic/geologic] These structural regimes broadly relate to convergent boundaries, divergent boundaries, and transform boundaries, respectively, between tectonic plates.
[src:geologic/geologic] When rock units are placed under horizontal compression, they shorten and become thicker.
[src:geologic/geologic] Because rock units, other than muds, do not significantly change in volume, this is accomplished in two primary ways: through faulting and folding.
[src:geologic/geologic] In the shallow crust, where brittle deformation can occur, thrust faults form, which causes the deeper rock to move on top of the shallower rock.
[src:geologic/geologic] Because deeper rock is often older, as noted by the principle of superposition, this can result in older rocks moving on top of younger ones.
[src:geologic/geologic] Movement along faults can result in folding, either because the faults are not planar or because rock layers are dragged along, forming drag folds as slip occurs along the fault.
[src:geologic/geologic] Deeper in the Earth, rocks behave plastically and fold instead of faulting.
[src:geologic/geologic] These folds can either be those where the material in the center of the fold buckles upwards, creating "antiforms", or where it buckles downwards, creating "synforms".
[src:geologic/geologic] If the tops of the rock units within the folds remain pointing upwards, they are called anticlines and synclines, respectively.
[src:geologic/geologic] If some of the units in the fold are facing downward, the structure is called an overturned anticline or syncline, and if all of the rock units are overturned or the correct up-direction is unknown, they are simply called by the most general terms, antiforms, and synforms.
[src:geologic/geologic] Even higher pressures and temperatures during horizontal shortening can cause both folding and metamorphism of the rocks.
[src:geologic/geologic] This metamorphism causes changes in the mineral composition of the rocks; creates a foliation, or planar surface, that is related to mineral growth under stress.
[src:geologic/geologic] This can remove signs of the original textures of the rocks, such as bedding in sedimentary rocks, flow features of lavas, and crystal patterns in crystalline rocks.
[src:geologic/geologic] Extension causes the rock units as a whole to become longer and thinner.
[src:geologic/geologic] This is primarily accomplished through normal faulting and through the ductile stretching and thinning.
[src:geologic/geologic] Normal faults drop rock units that are higher below those that are lower.
[src:geologic/geologic] This typically results in younger units ending up below older units.
[src:geologic/geologic] Stretching of units can result in their thinning.
[src:geologic/geologic] In fact, at one location within the Maria Fold and Thrust Belt, the entire sedimentary sequence of the Grand Canyon appears over a length of less than a meter.
[src:geologic/geologic] Rocks at the depth to be ductilely stretched are often metamorphosed.
[src:geologic/geologic] These stretched rocks can pinch into lenses, known as *boudins*, after the French word for "sausage" because of their visual similarity.
[src:geologic/geologic] Where rock units slide past one another, strike-slip faults develop in shallow regions, and become shear zones at deeper depths where the rocks deform ductilely.
[src:geologic/geologic] The addition of new rock units, both depositionally and intrusively, often occurs during deformation.
[src:geologic/geologic] Faulting and other deformational processes result in the creation of topographic gradients, causing material on the rock unit that is increasing in elevation to be eroded by hillslopes and channels.
[src:geologic/geologic] These sediments are deposited on the rock unit that is going down.
[src:geologic/geologic] Continual motion along the fault maintains the topographic gradient in spite of the movement of sediment and continues to create accommodation space for the material to deposit.
[src:geologic/geologic] Deformational events are often associated with volcanism and igneous activity.
[src:geologic/geologic] Volcanic ashes and lavas accumulate on the surface, and igneous intrusions enter from below.
[src:geologic/geologic] Dikes, long, planar igneous intrusions, enter along cracks, and therefore often form in large numbers in areas that are being actively deformed.
[src:geologic/geologic] This can result in the emplacement of dike swarms, such as those that are observable across the Canadian shield, or rings of dikes around the lava tube of a volcano.
[src:geologic/geologic] All of these processes do not necessarily occur in a single environment and do not necessarily occur in a single order.
[src:geologic/geologic] The Hawaiian Islands, for example, consist almost entirely of layered basaltic lava flows.
[src:geologic/geologic] The sedimentary sequences of the mid-continental United States and the Grand Canyon in the southwestern United States contain almost-undeformed stacks of sedimentary rocks that have remained in place since Cambrian time.
[src:geologic/geologic] Other areas are much more geologically complex.
[src:geologic/geologic] In the southwestern United States, sedimentary, volcanic, and intrusive rocks have been metamorphosed, faulted, foliated, and folded.
[src:geologic/geologic] Even older rocks, such as the Acasta gneiss of the Slave craton in northwestern Canada, the oldest known rock in the world have been metamorphosed to the point where their origin is indiscernible without laboratory analysis.
[src:geologic/geologic] In many places, the Grand Canyon in the southwestern United States being a very visible example, the lower rock units were metamorphosed and deformed, and then deformation ended and the upper, undeformed units were deposited.
[src:geologic/geologic] Although any amount of rock emplacement and rock deformation can occur, and they can occur any number of times, these concepts provide a guide to understanding the geological history of an area.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geologists use a number of fields, laboratory, and numerical modeling methods to decipher Earth history and to understand the processes that occur on and inside the Earth.
[src:geologic/geologic] In typical geological investigations, geologists use primary information related to petrology (the study of rocks), stratigraphy (the study of sedimentary layers), and structural geology (the study of positions of rock units and their deformation).
[src:geologic/geologic] In many cases, geologists study modern soils, rivers, landscapes, and glaciers; investigate past and current life and biogeochemical pathways, and use geophysical methods to investigate the subsurface.
[src:geologic/geologic] Sub-specialities of geology may distinguish *endogenous* and *exogenous* geology.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geological field work varies depending on the task at hand.
[src:geologic/geologic] , thin sections are used to study rocks.
[src:geologic/geologic] The method is based on the distinct refractive indexes of different minerals.
[src:geologic/geologic] In addition to identifying rocks in the field (lithology), petrologists identify rock samples in the laboratory.
[src:geologic/geologic] Two of the primary methods for identifying rocks in the laboratory are through optical microscopy (such as with the petrographic microscope) and by using an electron microprobe.
[src:geologic/geologic] In the electron microprobe, individual locations are analyzed for their exact chemical compositions and variation in composition within individual crystals.
[src:geologic/geologic] Stable and radioactive isotope studies provide insight into the geochemical evolution of rock units.
[src:geologic/geologic] Petrologists can use fluid inclusion data and perform high temperature and pressure physical experiments to understand the temperatures and pressures at which different mineral phases appear, and how they change through igneous and metamorphic processes.
[src:geologic/geologic] This research can be extrapolated to the field to understand metamorphic processes and the conditions of crystallization of igneous rocks.
[src:geologic/geologic] This work can help to explain processes that occur within the Earth, such as subduction and magma chamber evolution.
[src:geologic/geologic] Structural geologists use microscopic analysis of oriented thin sections of geological samples to observe the fabric within the rocks, which gives information about strain within the crystalline structure of the rocks.
[src:geologic/geologic] They plot and combine measurements of geological structures to better understand the orientations of faults and folds to reconstruct the history of rock deformation in the area.
[src:geologic/geologic] In addition, they perform analog and numerical experiments of rock deformation in large and small settings.
[src:geologic/geologic] The analysis of structures is often accomplished by plotting the orientations of various features onto stereonets.
[src:geologic/geologic] A stereonet is a stereographic projection of a sphere onto a plane, in which planes are projected as lines and lines are projected as points.
[src:geologic/geologic] These can be used to find the locations of fold axes, relationships between faults, and relationships between other geological structures.
[src:geologic/geologic] Among the most well-known experiments in structural geology are those involving orogenic wedges, which are zones in which mountains are built along convergent tectonic plate boundaries.
[src:geologic/geologic] In the analog versions of these experiments, horizontal layers of sand are pulled along a lower surface into a back stop, which results in realistic-looking patterns of faulting and the growth of a critically tapered (all angles remain the same) orogenic wedge.
[src:geologic/geologic] Numerical models work in the same way as these analog models, though they are often more sophisticated and can include patterns of erosion and uplift in the mountain belt.
[src:geologic/geologic] This helps to show the relationship between erosion and the shape of a mountain range.
[src:geologic/geologic] These studies can give useful information about pathways for metamorphism through pressure, temperature, space, and time.
[src:geologic/geologic] In the laboratory, stratigraphers analyze samples of stratigraphic sections that can be returned from the field, such as those from drill cores.
[src:geologic/geologic] Stratigraphers analyze data from geophysical surveys that show the locations of stratigraphic units in the subsurface.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geophysical data and well logs can be combined to produce a better view of the subsurface, and stratigraphers often use computer programs to do this in three dimensions.
[src:geologic/geologic] Stratigraphers can then use these data to reconstruct ancient processes occurring on the surface of the Earth, interpret past environments, and locate areas for water, coal, and hydrocarbon extraction.
[src:geologic/geologic] In the laboratory, biostratigraphers analyze rock samples from outcrop and drill cores for the fossils found in them.
[src:geologic/geologic] These fossils help scientists to date the core and to understand the depositional environment in which the rock units formed.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geochronologists precisely date rocks within the stratigraphic section to provide better absolute bounds on the timing and rates of deposition.
[src:geologic/geologic] Magnetic stratigraphers look for signs of magnetic reversals in igneous rock units within the drill cores.
[src:geologic/geologic] Other scientists perform stable-isotope studies on the rocks to gain information about past climate.
[src:geologic/geologic] With the advent of space exploration in the twentieth century, geologists have begun to look at other planetary bodies in the same ways that have been developed to study the Earth.
[src:geologic/geologic] This new field of study is called planetary geology (sometimes known as astrogeology) and relies on known geological principles to study other bodies of the Solar System.
[src:geologic/geologic] This is a major aspect of planetary science, and largely focuses on the terrestrial planets, icy moons, asteroids, comets, and meteorites.
[src:geologic/geologic] However, some planetary geophysicists study the giant planets and exoplanets.
[src:geologic/geologic] Although the Greek-language-origin prefix *geo* refers to Earth, "geology" is often used in conjunction with the names of other planetary bodies when describing their composition and internal processes: examples are "the geology of Mars" and "Lunar geology".
[src:geologic/geologic] Specialized terms such as *selenology* (studies of the Moon), *areology* (of Mars), *hermesology* (of Mercury), etc., are also in use.
[src:geologic/geologic] Although planetary geologists are interested in studying all aspects of other planets, a significant focus is to search for evidence of past or present life on other worlds.
[src:geologic/geologic] This has led to many missions whose primary or ancillary purpose is to examine planetary bodies for evidence of life.
[src:geologic/geologic] One of these is the Phoenix lander, which analyzed Martian polar soil for water, chemical, and mineralogical constituents related to biological processes.
[src:geologic/geologic] Economic geology is a branch of geology that deals with aspects of economic minerals that humankind uses to fulfill various needs.
[src:geologic/geologic] Economic minerals are those extracted profitably for various practical uses.
[src:geologic/geologic] Economic geologists help locate and manage the Earth's natural resources, such as petroleum and coal, as well as mineral resources, which include metals such as iron, copper, and uranium.
[src:geologic/geologic] Mining geology consists of the extractions of mineral and ore resources from the Earth.
[src:geologic/geologic] Some resources of economic interests include gemstones, metals such as gold and copper, and many industrial minerals such as asbestos, magnesite, perlite, mica, phosphates, zeolites, clay, silica, and pumice, as well as elements such as sulfur and helium.
[src:geologic/geologic] Petroleum geologists study the locations of the subsurface of the Earth that can contain extractable hydrocarbons, especially petroleum and natural gas.
[src:geologic/geologic] Because many of these reservoirs are found in sedimentary basins, they study the formation of these basins, their sedimentary and tectonic evolution, and the present-day positions of the rock units.
[src:geologic/geologic] Engineering geology is the application of geological principles to engineering practice for the purpose of assuring that the geological factors affecting the location, design, construction, operation, and maintenance of engineering works are properly addressed.
[src:geologic/geologic] Engineering geology is distinct from geological engineering, particularly in North America.
[src:geologic/geologic] In the field of civil engineering, geological principles and analyses are used in order to ascertain the mechanical principles of the material on which structures are built.
[src:geologic/geologic] This allows tunnels to be built without collapsing, bridges and skyscrapers to be built with sturdy foundations, and buildings to be built that will not settle in clay and mud.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geology and geological principles can be applied to various environmental problems such as stream restoration, the restoration of brownfields, and the understanding of the interaction between natural habitat and the geological environment.
[src:geologic/geologic] Groundwater hydrology, or hydrogeology, is used to locate groundwater, which can often provide a ready supply of uncontaminated water and is especially important in arid regions, and to monitor the spread of contaminants in groundwater wells.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geologists obtain data through stratigraphy, boreholes, core samples, and ice cores.
[src:geologic/geologic] Ice cores and sediment cores are used for paleoclimate reconstructions, which tell geologists about past and present temperature, precipitation, and sea level across the globe.
[src:geologic/geologic] These datasets are our primary source of information on global climate change outside of instrumental data.
[src:geologic/geologic] Geologists and geophysicists study natural hazards in order to enact safe building codes and warning systems that are used to prevent loss of property and life.
[src:geologic/geologic] The study of the physical material of the Earth dates back at least to ancient Greece when Theophrastus (372–287 BCE) wrote the work *Peri Lithon* (*On Stones*).
[src:geologic/geologic] During the Roman period, Pliny the Elder wrote in detail of the many minerals and metals, then in practical use – even correctly noting the origin of amber.
[src:geologic/geologic] Additionally, in the 4th century BCE Aristotle made critical observations of the slow rate of geological change.
[src:geologic/geologic] He observed the composition of the land and formulated a theory where the Earth changes at a slow rate and that these changes cannot be observed during one person's lifetime.
[src:geologic/geologic] Aristotle developed one of the first evidence-based concepts connected to the geological realm regarding the rate at which the Earth physically changes.
[src:geologic/geologic] Abu al-Rayhan al-Biruni (973–1048 CE) was one of the earliest Persian geologists, whose works included the earliest writings on the geology of India, hypothesizing that the Indian subcontinent was once a sea.
[src:geologic/geologic] Georgius Agricola (1494–1555) published his groundbreaking work *De Natura Fossilium* in 1546 and is seen as the founder of geology as a scientific discipline.
[src:geologic/geologic] Nicolas Steno (1638–1686) is credited with the law of superposition, the principle of original horizontality, and the principle of lateral continuity: three defining principles of stratigraphy.
[src:geologic/geologic] The word *geology* was first used by Ulisse Aldrovandi in 1603, then by Jean-André Deluc in 1778 and introduced as a fixed term by Horace-Bénédict de Saussure in 1779.
[src:geologic/geologic] The word is derived from the Greek γῆ, *gê*, meaning "earth" and λόγος, *logos*, meaning "speech".
[src:geologic/geologic] But according to another source, the word "geology" comes from a Norwegian, Mikkel Pedersøn Escholt (1600–1669), who was a priest and scholar.
[src:geologic/geologic] Escholt first used the definition in his book titled, *Geologia Norvegica* (1657).
[src:geologic/geologic] William Smith (1769–1839) drew some of the first geological maps and began the process of ordering rock strata (layers) by examining the fossils contained in them.
[src:geologic/geologic] In 1763, Mikhail Lomonosov published his treatise *On the Strata of Earth*.
[src:geologic/geologic] His work was the first narrative of modern geology, based on the unity of processes in time and explanation of the Earth's past from the present.
[src:geologic/geologic] James Hutton (1726–1797) is often viewed as the first modern geologist.
[src:geologic/geologic] In 1785 he presented a paper entitled *Theory of the Earth* to the Royal Society of Edinburgh.
[src:geologic/geologic] In his paper, he explained his theory that the Earth must be much older than had previously been supposed to allow enough time for mountains to be eroded and for sediments to form new rocks at the bottom of the sea, which in turn were raised up to become dry land.
[src:geologic/geologic] Hutton published a two-volume version of his ideas in 1795.
[src:geologic/geologic] The first geological map of the U.S. was produced in 1809 by William Maclure.
[src:geologic/geologic] In 1807, Maclure commenced the self-imposed task of making a geological survey of the United States.
[src:geologic/geologic] Almost every state in the Union was traversed and mapped by him, the Allegheny Mountains being crossed and recrossed some 50 times.
[src:geologic/geologic] The results of his unaided labours were submitted to the American Philosophical Society in a memoir entitled *Observations on the Geology of the United States explanatory of a Geological Map*, and published in the *Society's Transactions*, together with the nation's first geological map.
[src:geologic/geologic] This antedates William Smith's geological map of England by six years, although it was constructed using a different classification of rocks.
[src:geologic/geologic] Sir Charles Lyell (1797–1875) first published his famous book, *Principles of Geology*, in 1830.
[src:geologic/geologic] This book, which influenced the thought of Charles Darwin, successfully promoted the doctrine of uniformitarianism.
[src:geologic/geologic] This theory states that slow geological processes have occurred throughout the Earth's history and are still occurring today.
[src:geologic/geologic] In contrast, catastrophism is the theory that Earth's features formed in single, catastrophic events and remained unchanged thereafter.
[src:geologic/geologic] Though Hutton believed in uniformitarianism, the idea was not widely accepted at the time.
[src:geologic/geologic] Much of 19th-century geology revolved around the question of the Earth's exact age.
[src:geologic/geologic] Estimates varied from a few hundred thousand to billions of years.
[src:geologic/geologic] By the early 20th century, radiometric dating allowed the Earth's age to be estimated at two billion years.
[src:geologic/geologic] The awareness of this vast amount of time opened the door to new theories about the processes that shaped the planet.
[src:geologic/geologic] Some of the most significant advances in 20th-century geology have been the development of the theory of plate tectonics in the 1960s and the refinement of estimates of the planet's age.
[src:geologic/geologic] Plate tectonics theory arose from two separate geological observations: seafloor spreading and continental drift.
[src:geologic/geologic] The theory revolutionized the Earth sciences.
[src:geologic/geologic] Today the Earth is known to be approximately 4.5 billion years old.
[src:geologic/noun] In grammar, a **noun** is a word that represents a concrete or abstract thing, like living creatures, places, actions, events, qualities, states of existence, and ideas.
[src:geologic/noun] To summarize this, nouns signify an object or idea.
[src:geologic/noun] A noun may serve as an object or subject within a phrase, clause, or sentence.
[src:geologic/noun] In linguistics, nouns constitute a lexical category (part of speech) defined according to how its members combine with members of other lexical categories.
[src:geologic/noun] The syntactic occurrence of nouns differs among languages.
[src:geologic/noun] In English, prototypical nouns are common nouns or proper nouns that can occur with determiners, articles and attributive adjectives, and can function as the head of a noun phrase.
[src:geologic/noun] According to traditional and popular classification, pronouns are distinct from nouns, but in much modern theory they are considered a subclass of nouns.
[src:geologic/noun] Every language has various linguistic and grammatical distinctions between nouns and verbs.
[src:geologic/noun] Word classes (parts of speech) were described by Sanskrit grammarians from at least the 5th century BC.
[src:geologic/noun] In Yāska's *Nirukta*, the noun (*nāma*) is one of the four main categories of words defined.
[src:geologic/noun] The Ancient Greek equivalent was *ónoma* (ὄνομα), referred to by Plato in the *Cratylus*, and later listed as one of the eight parts of speech in *The Art of Grammar*, attributed to Dionysius Thrax (2nd century BC).
[src:geologic/noun] The term used in Latin grammar was *nōmen*.
[src:geologic/noun] All of these terms for "noun" were also words meaning "name".
[src:geologic/noun] The English word *noun* is derived from the Latin term, through the Anglo-Norman *nom* (other forms include *nomme*, and *noun* itself).
[src:geologic/noun] The word classes were defined partly by the grammatical forms that they take.
[src:geologic/noun] In Sanskrit, Greek, and Latin, for example, nouns are categorized by gender and inflected for case and number.
[src:geologic/noun] Because adjectives share these three grammatical categories, adjectives typically were placed in the same class as nouns.
[src:geologic/noun] Similarly, the Latin term *nōmen* includes both nouns (substantives) and adjectives, as originally did the English word *noun*, the two types being distinguished as *nouns substantive* and *nouns adjective* (or *substantive nouns* and *adjective nouns*, or simply *substantives* and *adjectives*).
[src:geologic/noun] Many European languages use a cognate of the word *substantive* as the basic term for *noun* (for example, Spanish *sustantivo*, "noun").
[src:geologic/noun] Nouns in the dictionaries of such languages are demarked by the abbreviation *s.* or *sb.* instead of *n.*, which may be used for proper nouns or neuter nouns instead.
[src:geologic/noun] In English, some modern authors use the word *substantive* to refer to a class that includes both nouns (single words) and noun phrases (multiword units that are sometimes called *noun equivalents*).
[src:geologic/noun] It can also be used as a counterpart to *attributive* when distinguishing between a noun being used as the head (main word) of a noun phrase and a noun being used as a noun adjunct.
[src:geologic/noun] For example, the noun *knee* can be said to be used substantively in *my knee hurts*, but attributively in *the patient needed knee replacement*.
[src:geologic/noun] A noun can co-occur with an article or an attributive adjective.
[src:geologic/noun] In the following, an asterisk (*) in front of an example means that this example is ungrammatical.
[src:geologic/noun] Nouns have sometimes been characterized in terms of the grammatical categories by which they may be varied (for example gender, case, and number).
[src:geologic/noun] Such definitions tend to be language-specific, since different languages may apply different categories.
[src:geologic/noun] Nouns are frequently defined, particularly in informal contexts, in terms of their semantic properties (their meanings).
[src:geologic/noun] Nouns are described as words that refer to a *person*, *place*, *thing*, *event*, *substance*, *quality*, *quantity*, etc., but this manner of definition has been criticized as uninformative.
[src:geologic/noun] Several English nouns lack an intrinsic referent of their own: *behalf* (as in *on behalf of*), *dint* (*by dint of*), and *sake* (*for the sake of*).
[src:geologic/noun] Moreover, other parts of speech may have reference-like properties: the verbs *to rain* or *to mother*, or adjectives like *red*; and there is little difference between the adverb *gleefully* and the prepositional phrase *with glee*.
[src:geologic/noun] A functional approach defines a noun as a word that can be the head of a nominal phrase, i.e., a phrase with referential function, without needing to go through morphological transformation.
[src:geologic/noun] Nouns can have a number of different properties and are often sub-categorized based on various of these criteria, depending on their occurrence in a language.
[src:geologic/noun] Nouns may be classified according to morphological properties such as which prefixes or suffixes they take, and also their relations in syntax – how they combine with other words and expressions of various types.
[src:geologic/noun] Many such classifications are language-specific, given the obvious differences in syntax and morphology.
[src:geologic/noun] In English for example, it might be noted that nouns are words that can co-occur with definite articles (as stated at the start of this article), but this could not apply in Russian, which has no definite articles.
[src:geologic/noun] In some languages common and proper nouns have grammatical gender, typically masculine, feminine, and neuter.
[src:geologic/noun] The gender of a noun (as well as its number and case, where applicable) will often require agreement in words that modify or are used along with it.
[src:geologic/noun] In French for example, the singular form of the definite article is *le* for masculine nouns and *la* for feminine; adjectives and certain verb forms also change (sometimes with the simple addition of *-e* for feminine).
[src:geologic/noun] Grammatical gender often correlates with the form of the noun and the inflection pattern it follows; for example, in both Italian and Romanian most nouns ending in *-a* are feminine.
[src:geologic/noun] Gender can also correlate with the sex or social gender of the noun's referent, particularly in the case of nouns denoting people (and sometimes animals), though with exceptions (the feminine French noun *personne* can refer to a male or a female person).
[src:geologic/noun] In Modern English, even common nouns like *hen* and *princess* and proper nouns like *Alicia* do not have grammatical gender (their femininity has no relevance in syntax), though they denote persons or animals of a specific sex.
[src:geologic/noun] The gender of a pronoun must be appropriate for the item referred to: "The *girl* said the *ring* was from *her* new *boyfriend*, but *he* denied *it* was from *him*" (three nouns; and three gendered pronouns: or four, if this *her* is counted as a possessive pronoun).
[src:geologic/noun] Many nouns have both countable and uncountable uses; for example, *soda* is countable in "give me three sodas", but uncountable in "he likes soda".
[src:geologic/noun] Some nouns have both concrete and abstract meanings: *art* usually refers to something abstract ("Art is important in human culture"), but it can also refer to a concrete item ("I put my daughter's art up on the fridge").
[src:geologic/noun] A noun might have a literal (concrete) and also a figurative (abstract) meaning: "a brass *key*" and "the *key* to success"; "a *block* in the pipe" and "a mental *block*".
[src:geologic/noun] Similarly, some abstract nouns have developed etymologically by figurative extension from literal roots (*drawback*, *fraction*, *holdout*, *uptake*).
[src:geologic/noun] Many abstract nouns in English are formed by adding a suffix (*-ness*, *-ity*, *-ion*) to adjectives or verbs (*happiness* and *serenity* from the adjectives *happy* and *serene*; *circulation* from the verb *circulate*).
[src:geologic/noun] Illustrating the wide range of possible classifying principles for nouns, the Awa language of Papua New Guinea regiments nouns according to how *ownership* is assigned: as alienable possession or inalienable possession.
[src:geologic/noun] An alienably possessed item (a tree, for example) can exist even without a possessor.
[src:geologic/noun] But inalienably possessed items are necessarily associated with their possessor and are referred to differently, for example with nouns that function as kin terms (meaning "father", etc.), body-part nouns (meaning "shadow", "hair", etc.), or part–whole nouns (meaning "top", "bottom", etc.).
[src:geologic/noun] A noun phrase (or **NP**) is a phrase usually headed by a common noun, a proper noun, or a pronoun.
[src:geologic/noun] The head may be the only constituent, or it may be modified by determiners and adjectives.
[src:geologic/noun] For example, "The dog sat near Ms Curtis and wagged its tail" contains three NPs: *the dog* (subject of the verbs *sat* and *wagged*); *Ms Curtis* (complement of the preposition *near*); and *its tail* (object of *wagged*).
[src:geologic/noun] "You became their teacher" contains two NPs: *you* (subject of *became*); and *their teacher*.
[src:geologic/noun] For example, in the sentence "Gareth thought she was weird", the word *she* is a pronoun that refers to a person just as the noun *Gareth* does.
[src:geologic/noun] The word *one* can replace parts of noun phrases, and it sometimes stands in for a noun.
[src:geologic/noun] But *one* can also stand in for larger parts of a noun phrase.
[src:geologic/noun] For example, in the following example, *one* can stand in for *new car*.
[src:geologic/noun] Nominalization is a process whereby a word that belongs to another part of speech comes to be used as a noun.
[src:geologic/noun] This can be a way to create new nouns, or to use other words in ways that resemble nouns.
[src:geologic/noun] In French and Spanish, for example, adjectives frequently act as nouns referring to people who have the characteristics denoted by the adjective.
[src:geologic/noun] is a worldwide association of political parties.
